    <blockquote><p>What would happen if someone deliberately broadcast huge numbers of  valid transactions as fast as his computer would allow? For example,  repeatedly transferring a single bitcoin back and forth between a set of  valid addresses? There must be some limit to the number of transactions  that the system can process per second.</p>
<p>Secondly, since the peers broadcast their IP addresses to everyone, a  hacker would know all of the peers at any one time and could send the  valid transactions to every peer, perhaps using a network of bots.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>To do that they would have to pay a minimal fee for each transaction. Anyone doing that would run out of coin fast enough.</p>
<blockquote><p>Also since the IPs of all of the inputs to the Bitcoin network at any  given time are known, a government would only need to monitor those IPs  in order to attach an IP address to every transaction. So it easily  track Bitcoin flows across IP addresses.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>People can use public website to broadcast their transaction. They can even broadcast them through the Tor network.</p>

